  <prompt>
    Run the `/doc-drift-audit` skill on the entire repo to detect orphaned references to retired components after Waves 0–6. Fix any orphans found. Document the audit results in `notes/research/093-doc-drift-audit.md` for the Wave 6 PR description.

    Specifically look for orphans referencing:
    - `sprk_communication_send.js` (retired in tasks 081, 082, 083)
    - The two RETIRED architecture docs (banners added in task 090) — verify no doc treats them as canonical
    - LegalWorkspace forks (deleted across Waves 3–5; final audit in task 084)
    - Any stale `sprk_email*` field references missed by task 091
    - Old send-email pattern references (replaced in task 086)
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Spaarke documentation hygiene specialist. Familiar with the `/doc-drift-audit` skill's diff-based audit pattern and the typical orphan classes that emerge after a multi-wave deletion + documentation update project.
  </role>

  <goal>
    Doc drift audit complete with zero unresolved orphan references to retired components. Audit results documented in `notes/research/093-doc-drift-audit.md`. Wave 6 PR description references the audit.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      Per FR-27 acceptance: "doc-drift-audit skill confirms no orphaned references". The skill scans for stale references in docs and `.claude/` that no longer match current code. After R3's 6 waves of deletions + 13 documentation updates, residual orphans are likely.

      The `doc-drift-audit` skill is designed for exactly this scenario — a compact, diff-based alternative to a full-repo audit.
    </background>
